Sure, here's an example of how you could create a webpage that displays a random video from your CSV file. This is a simple HTML, CSS and JavaScript page:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>BloomTube</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }
        .video-container {
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            margin-top: 30px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>BloomTube</h1>
    <div class="video-container">
        <iframe id="randomVideo" width="560" height="315" src="" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>
        <h2 id="songName"></h2>
        <p id="artist"></p>
        <p id="characterStrength"></p>
        <p id="reasoning"></p>
    </div>
    <button onclick="randomVideo()">Play Another</button>

    <script>
        const data = [
            ['Still','The Japanese House','Appreciation of Beauty & Excellence','The lyrics of the song express a sense of wonder and appreciation for the beauty of the world which is a key component of \'Appreciation of Beauty & Excellence\'. Additionally the instrumental composition has a dreamy and ethereal quality which further evokes a sense of awe and admiration.','https://www.youtube.com/embed/UW8pDDhrtkQ'],
            // ... Include all other rows from the CSV here
        ];

        function randomVideo() {
            const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * data.length);
            const video = data[randomIndex];
            document.getElementById('randomVideo').src = video[4];
            document.getElementById('songName').textContent = video[0];
            document.getElementById('artist').textContent = 'Artist: ' + video[1];
            document.getElementById('characterStrength').textContent = 'Character Strength: ' + video[2];
            document.getElementById('reasoning').textContent = 'Reasoning: ' + video[3];
        }

        // Play a video when the page loads
        window.onload = randomVideo;
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This simple webpage is using JavaScript to select a random row from the `data` array (which represents the CSV data) when the page loads, and when the "Play Another" button is clicked. It then updates the `src` attribute of the iframe (which is displaying the YouTube video), as well as the text content of the song name, artist, character strength, and reasoning elements.

Remember to replace `// ... Include all other rows from the CSV here` with the rest of your data from your CSV, and note that the YouTube URLs are changed to their embed versions (replacing `watch?v=` with `embed/`). This allows the videos to be embedded directly into the webpage.

